const HAR_MACRO = `Hi {{ticket.requester.first_name}},

Thanks for reaching out to Klaviyo Support! My name is {{current_user.first_name}}, and I'm happy to help get this sorted out for you.

To make sure our engineering team has everything they need to dig into this, I'd like to ask you to capture a HAR file — this is a quick browser recording that helps us see exactly what's happening behind the scenes when the issue occurs.
 
Before you start recording, please make sure you're already logged into any accounts or tools you'll need — logging in during the recording can add noise to the file and make it harder for us to find the relevant activity.
 
Here's how to generate one (Please scroll to your respective browser for details):
 
Chrome:

1. Open Google Chrome and go to the page where the issue is occurring.
2. Look for the Vertical ellipsis button and select More Tools > Developer Tools. Alternatively you can control/ctr + left click > inspect from your browser.
3. From the inspector panel opened, select the Network tab.
4. (optional) Click the Clear button to clear any existing logs from the Network tab.
5. Check the box Preserve log.
6. Look for a round Record button in the upper left corner of the tab, and make sure it is red. If it is grey, click it once to start recording.
7. Reproduce the issue that you were experiencing while the network requests are being recorded.
8. Once you have reproduced the issue, right-click anywhere on the grid of network requests, select Save as HAR with Content, and save the file to your computer.
9. For security reasons, support team is unable to download attachments directly, so please share this HAR file via an online tool, like Dropbox or Google Drive.
            
Firefox:

1. Open Firefox and go to the page where you are experiencing trouble.
2. Click the Firefox menu (three horizontal parallel lines) at the top right of your browser window, then select More Tools > Browser Console. You can also use Option + ⌘ + E (on macOS) or Shift + CTRL + C (on Windows/Linux)
3. Web Developer > Network.
4. Refresh the page.
5. The Developer Network Tools opens as a docked panel at the side or bottom of Firefox. Click the Network tab.
6. The recording auto-starts when you start performing actions in the browser.
7. Once you have reproduced the issue and see that all of the actions have been generated in the Developer Network Panel (it should just take a few seconds), right-click anywhere under the File column or click the settings icon (upper right side of the panel) and click on Save all as Har.
8. Save the HAR file somewhere convenient.
9. For security reasons, we are unable to download attachments, so please share it via an online tool, like Dropbox or Google Drive so that our Support team can analyze it.
 
 
Internet Explorer:

1. Open Internet Explorer and go to the page where the issue is occurring.
2. Press F12 on your keyboard (or click the gear icon > F12 Developer Tools)
3. Click the Network tab.
4. Reproduce the issue that you were experiencing before, while the network requests are being recorded.
5. Once done click the Save button.
6. Give the trace a filename and click the Save button which will save it as a .har file or .xml file.
7. For security reasons, we are unable to download attachments, so please share it via an online tool, like Dropbox or Google Drive so that our Support team can analyze it.
 
Microsoft Edge

1. Open Microsoft Edge and go to the page where the issue is occurring.
2. Press F12 to open the debug pane (or click the gear icon > F12 Developer Tools).
3. Clear the session history before reproducing.
4. Press the play button at the top left of the debug pane to start recording.
5. Reproduce the issue.
6. Press the red square to stop recording.
7. Export the results as a HAR file by right-clicking anywhere on the grid of network requests and selecting Save all as a HAR file.
8. For security reasons, we are unable to download attachments, so please share it via an online tool, like Dropbox or Google Drive so that our Support team can analyze it.
 
Safari:
Before generating the HAR file, make sure you can see the Develop menu in Safari. If it is not there, follow the instructions under Use the Developer tools in the Develop menu in Safari on Mac (https://support.apple.com/en-ie/guide/safari/use-the-developer-tools-in-the-develop-menu-sfri20948/mac).

1. Open the Develop menu and select Show Web Inspector.
   1. If you don't see the Develop menu,  click Safari > Settings, click Advanced, then select "Show features for web developers" and the Develop menu > Show Web Inspector will appear.
2. Click the Network tab and complete the activity causing issues.
3. Click the Export icon on the far right of the network tab and save the HAR file.
4. For security reasons, we cannot download attachments, so please share them via an online tool, like Dropbox or Google Drive, so that our Support team can analyze them.
I look forward to your response!`;

